seems I can't scan test-compiled classes with the older Spring version. I'm considering using an alternative method that covers the auto-configured registrar without performing an actual classpath scan. Is MybatisPlusAutoConfiguration.AutoConfiguredMapperScannerRegistrar a viable option since it's a public static inner class? I might try using AnnotationConfigApplicationContext with registered AutoConfigurationPackages pointing only to compatible compiled classes, avoiding @Mapper. This way, the MapperScannerConfigurer will handle scanning without duplication in functionality, though testing will be necessary to validate whether automatic mapper scanning gets disabled.\\n\\n**Validating Mapper Scanning Setup**\\n\\nI think the setup is looking for the @Mapper annotation within the specified package. If there are no mappers, the context starts, but I need to ensure the MapperScannerConfigurer bean is properly configured. Upon context refresh, this bean scans the specified package, assuming it doesn't contain incompatible classes. Using \\\"org.apache.ibatis.annotations\\\" could work since those classes are likely compiled in Java 8 and should be parseable, but I'm unsure if it will actually find the @Mapper interfaces. There seems to be more involved with the starter registering the scanner configurer, creating a functional feature.\\n\\n**Evaluating Spring Boot Annotations**\\n\\nI'm considering whether the ApplicationContextRunner can provide an @AutoConfigurationPackage class within a package. It seems that this annotation registers only the packages of annotated classes. To choose a dependency package, I might need to use @AutoConfigurationPackage with basePackages. I should look into Spring Boot 2.5 to see if this annotation offers basePackages. Maybe I can check its implementation, possibly by using javap, since it likely does based on Spring Boot 2.3.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_02a81ebd13c1d321016a2530970e8881909a94ef22f7b74aef\\\",\\\"typ